        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We seek detections of lines listed in Table 1 which have already been detected using Herschel/HIFI. Fig. 3 plots these lines along with Gaussian fits to the different spatial/velocity components. Using the HIFI single dish observations as a guide, we request a sensitivity of 0.32 K (or 100.14 mJy). The 9_{7,2}-9_{6,3} transition sets our sensitivity goal because it is the weakest in our sample. Based on the highly optically thick low energy H2S lines, we estimate an effective source size of 6", which is probably too large for the J=9 transition because the most highly excited lines likely trace more compact structure than the lower energy lines. Other molecular tracers toward the hot core, furthermore, reveal compact, clumpy structure on spatial scales as small as 1" (e.g. Beuther et al. 2005, Wang et al. 2010, Goddi et al. 2011). We therefore conservatively assume a source size of 4" and obtain an intrinsic peak line intensity of 32 K. Assuming a uniform surface brightness, this will yield a 5 sigma detection in the proposed ALMA observations. Given that the maximum recoverable scale is ~3.9" at 687~GHz in the most compact 12-m array configuration, we request complementary ACA observations to recover any flux that is resolved out by the 12-m array. This will make comparisons between the J=2/4 and J=9 maps more reliable. Because we seek spectral line observations at a spectral resolution of approximately 0.4 km/s, we choose the Representative Window Resolution as the bandwidth used for our sensitivity calculation. According to the ALMA Observing Tool, the 12m array and ACA observations can be obtained in 1.31 and 2.62 hours, respectively. The total requested observing time is therefore 3.93 hours.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We seek detections of lines listed in Table 1, which can all be obtained at a single LO setting. We only require 3 basebands because the 2_{0,2}-1_{1,1} transitions of H2S-32 and H2S-33 lie within the same baseband. We do not attempt to observe the H2S-34 2_{0,2}-1_{1,1} transition because it is heavily blended with a line from a different molecule. We have already detected these lines using Herschel/HIFI. Fig. 3 plots these lines along with Gaussian fits to the different spatial/velocity components. From the plot, we see that, in addition to the hot core the low energy H2S-32 J=2 line also contains emission from the extended ridge and plateau. The other transitions contain emission exclusively from the hot core. Table 1 gives the rest frequencies and upper state energies of these transitions as well as observed velocities, line widths, and peak intensities for the hot core spatial/velocity component. The observed line widths for the transitions in our sample are &gt;7 km/s (see Table 1). We therefore chose the correlator setting with 976.563 KHz (~0.4 km/s) resolution, which will easily resolve each line. 
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We propose here to perform a 20" x 20" mosaic that will image the brightest mid-IR clumps as well as all alleged internally heated sources toward Orion KL. The field of interest is roughly square. Hence, we request that a Nyquist sampled square mosaic, (totaling 27 and 10 pointings for the 12 and 7m arrays, respectively), be carried out to produce reliable interferometric maps of all lines. The IR clumps are separated on scales &gt;1-2" (see Fig. 1). We therefore request a spatial resolution of 0.9", which will be sufficient to unambiguously determine if H2S emission is co-spatial with any known color temperature peaks or IR clumps. Given that the maximum recoverable size scale is ~3.9" at 687 GHz in the most compact 12-m array configuration, we request complementary ACA observations to recover any flux that is resolved out by the 12-m array. This will make comparisons between the J=2/4 and J=9 maps more reliable. 

We note that the main purpose of this proposal is to use H2S as a tracer of dense gas that is heavily irradiated by hot dust, possibly surrounding embedded massive protostars. For this reason, the 9_{7,2}-9_{6,3} map, which is less likely to have resolved out flux due to its presumably more compact structure, is the most relevant observation. Calibration issues associated with Cycle 3 ACA observations in band 9, which may affect to a greater extent the more extended J=2 and 4 maps, will therefore not threaten our main science goal of locating the major sources of luminosity in Orion KL.
</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
